Your project becomes “dynamic” mainly because of JavaScript doing 4 things repeatedly across pages:

Storing data in the browser (localStorage) like a mini-database (users, bookings, payments, session).
Listening to user actions (form submit, dropdown change, button click).
Generating HTML on the fly using template strings and inserting it into the page (innerHTML).
Routing/controlling access by redirecting users depending on login + role.
Below is the full functional logic (only JavaScript/dynamic behavior), explained in layman language, page-by-page and file-by-file.

1) The “Engine” of the project: js/main.js (Global HMS object)
This file creates a global object window.HMS which is like the core service layer used everywhere.

A) LocalStorage as a database
getUsers() / setUsers(users)
getBookings() / setBookings(bookings)
getPayments() / setPayments(payments)
getCurrentUser() / setCurrentUser(user)
How it works (layman):

localStorage is permanent browser memory (until cleared).
Data must be stored as strings, so the code uses:
JSON.stringify(object) before saving
JSON.parse(string) after reading
So instead of a server/database, the whole app runs like a frontend-only mock system.

B) Session management (login stays active)
setCurrentUser() stores a trimmed session object in localStorage under the key "session".
getCurrentUser() reads it back.
logout() removes "session" and sends you back to index.html.
Why it makes the app dynamic: Because every page checks session and decides:

“Allow this user” or
“Kick back to login” or
“Redirect based on role”
C) checkAuth(rolesAllowed)
This is the gatekeeper used on almost every page.

Logic:

If there is no logged-in user → redirect to index.html
If the user role is not allowed on that page → redirect to dashboard.html
Else return the user object
Viva-ready line: “Every page is protected by a client-side auth guard that checks a session object in localStorage.”

D) renderNavbar()
Navbar links are not hard-coded; they are injected via JS depending on role.

Admin gets extra links like Room Status, Reservation management, etc.
Customer gets limited links.
Then it highlights the active link using:

link.classList.add('active')
Why it’s dynamic: Same HTML navbar placeholder, but content differs based on who logged in.

E) showAlert(msg, type)
Displays messages inside an element (usually #alertBox) dynamically:

sets textContent
changes class name: alert success or alert error
shows it for 5 seconds using setTimeout
Viva tip: If manager asks “How alerts disappear automatically?” Answer: “A timer (setTimeout) hides it after 5 seconds.”

F) showModal(modalId) / hideModal(modalId)
Adds/removes the CSS class active to show/hide modal overlays.

G) Data cleanup / compatibility: migrateStorage()
This is a “migration script” that:

checks for older storage keys (hms_currentUser, userData, hms_users, etc.)
merges them into the new standard keys (session, users, bookings, payments)
removes junk keys (like those starting with acc_)
In simple words: “If someone used an older version of this app, their browser storage is upgraded automatically.”

H) seedAdmin()
If no admin exists, it auto-creates one:

userId: admin
password: Admin@123
Must know for viva: This is how your app guarantees an admin exists even in a fresh browser.

2) Authentication logic: js/auth.js (Register + Login)
This file defines window.HMS_Auth.

A) Password validation using Regex
validatePassword(pwd) uses a regular expression:

at least 1 lowercase
at least 1 uppercase
at least 1 special character
minimum length 8
Layman explanation: Regex is a “pattern checker.” It checks if the password matches the security rules.

B) Register flow: register(data)
Steps:

Check password strength
Check confirm password matches
Check if userId already exists (duplicate prevention)
Create new user object
Push into users array → save to localStorage
Returns success/failure messages that pages show using HMS.showAlert.

C) Login flow: login(userId, password, role)
Steps:

Read all users from localStorage
Find a matching user with same id + password + role
If found:
Store session {userId, name, role} only (not the whole user record)
Return success/failure
Important point: This app is not using hashing or server auth; it’s a mock frontend auth.

3) Reservation logic: js/reservation.js (Bookings lifecycle)
This file defines window.HMS_Reservation.

A) Room pricing table
roomPrices is basically the rate card used to compute bill.

B) calculateDays(checkIn, checkOut)
Converts strings to Date objects
Subtracts dates to get milliseconds
converts to days
ensures minimum 1 day
Layman: “Date subtraction gives time difference; then we convert it into number of nights.”

C) createBooking(...)
Creates a booking object like:

bookingId (generated)
userId, name, contact
checkIn, checkOut
roomType
roomNumber: null initially
billAmount computed
status: 'pending'
bookingDate: current time
Then it saves into localStorage.

Viva-ready: “Booking is created in ‘pending’ state; admin later approves and assigns a room.”

D) updateBookingStatus(bookingId, status, roomNumber)
Admin actions call this to move booking through:

pending → approved (with room number)
approved → checked-in
checked-out after payment (in billing logic)
rejected
4) Billing & payment logic: js/billing.js
Defines window.HMS_Billing.

A) getLatestBooking(userId)
Finds last active booking for a user (ignores checked-out and rejected).

B) generateInvoice(bookingId)
Computes:

baseCharge = booking.billAmount
taxes = 18% of base (mock GST)
extra charges (room service etc.)
grand total = base + taxes + extras
Key concept: Invoice is calculated dynamically each time, not stored permanently.

C) addExtraCharge(bookingId, amount)
Adds extra charges into booking object and saves.

D) processPayment(bookingId, amount)
Creates a payment entry:

transactionId
bookingId
userId
amount
status: paid
Then for mock simplicity it auto checks out the booking:

HMS_Reservation.updateBookingStatus(bookingId, 'checked-out')
Viva: “Once payment is successful, booking status is updated to checked-out.”

Page-by-page “dynamic behavior” (inline scripts)
index.html (Login page)
Dynamic parts:

On load: if session already exists → redirect to dashboard.html
On submit: prevent page reload, read input values, call HMS_Auth.login()
Show error alert or redirect on success
Trigger: DOMContentLoaded, form submit
State read/write: reads users/session; writes session

register.html
On form submit: prevent reload
build a data object from inputs
call HMS_Auth.register(data)
show success/error
redirect to login after 2 seconds on success (setTimeout)
Trigger: form submit
State write: users array in localStorage

dashboard.html
On load:

checkAuth()
renderNavbar()
Reads bookings/users/payments and updates dashboard numbers.
Customer view shows:

total bookings
pending bookings count
Admin view shows:

total customers
pending reservations count
total revenue = sum of all payment amounts (reduce)
Trigger: page load
Dynamic: updates text of <h3> values

reservation.html
Two modes:

Customer:
Shows booking form
Sets minimum date to today for date inputs
Auto-fills guest name from session
On submit:
validates check-out after check-in
calls createBooking()
shows booking id
Admin:
Generates table using .map() + template strings
For pending bookings: shows dropdown with actions
Uses a global function window.handleAction(...)
Approve → asks room number using prompt()
Updates status and re-renders table
Key dynamic concept: Admin table isn’t static HTML; it’s generated from booking objects.

billing.html
Two modes:

Customer:
loads latest booking
if approved/checked-in: generates invoice UI dynamically
“Pay Bill” button redirects to payment page with query params: payment.html?bId=...&amt=...
Admin:
search userId
shows invoice
can add mock charges, then re-renders invoice
Dynamic pieces:

conditional rendering (no active booking → show message)
generating full invoice HTML via innerHTML
payment.html
reads URL query parameters using URLSearchParams
if missing bId/amt → show error and disable Pay button
shows amount
on submit:
calls processPayment() to create txn + checkout booking
displays transaction id
shows modal (CSS class toggle)
Trigger: form submit
State write: payments + booking status

bookings.html
Loads bookings based on role:
customer → only their bookings
admin → all bookings
Filters to upcoming/active (pending/approved/checked-in)
Renders cards dynamically using map().join('')
history.html
Customer automatically sees their history.
Admin sees a search form, enters a userId and fetches that user’s bookings.
Renders booking rows with formatted date: new Date(b.bookingDate).toLocaleDateString()
room-status.html
Creates mock room list in JS (not stored)
Reads bookings and marks rooms:
Booked if any active booking assigned to that room
Vacant otherwise
Allows filtering by Customer ID
Renders table dynamically
Key logic: It “joins” room list with active bookings to compute status.

support.html
Auto-fills customer ID if role is customer
On submit:
shows success alert
resets form
re-fills customer id again
This page is mostly UI mock (no storage/network), but still dynamic due to form handling.

Must-know points for your viva (high impact)
There is no backend.
All persistence is localStorage (users/bookings/payments/session). Mention it confidently.

Session auth is client-side only.
checkAuth() protects pages using the session key.

Role-based UI exists.
Same pages, but content and navbar change based on user.role.

Dynamic rendering pattern used everywhere:

get data array
filter/transform it
build HTML using template strings
inject using innerHTML
Reservation lifecycle (this is the story to tell):
Customer creates booking → pending
Admin approves + assigns room → approved
Admin checks-in customer → checked-in
Customer pays bill → payment saved + booking becomes checked-out
History page shows the trail
IDs are generated randomly.
generateId(prefix) is used for Booking IDs and Transaction IDs.

Admin account is auto-created. If no admin exists, the system seeds:

user: admin
pass: Admin@123
